SIMPLE: frolic
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Frolic
<hw>Frol"ic</hw> <pr>(fr⟦ocr⟧l"⟦icr⟧k)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[D.
<ets>vroolijk</ets>; akin to G. <ets>fr⟦oum⟧lich</ets>, fr.
<ets>froh</ets>, OHG. <ets>fr⟦omac⟧</ets>, Dan. <ets>fro</ets>, OS.
<ets>fr⟦amac⟧h</ets>, cf. Icel. <ets>fr⟦amac⟧r</ets> swift; all perh.
akin to Skr. <ets>pru</ets> to spring up.]</ety> <def>Full of levity;
dancing, playing, or frisking about; full of pranks; frolicsome; gay;
merry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>frolic</qex> wind that breathes the spring.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The gay, the <qex>frolic</qex>, and the loud.</q>
<rj><qau>Waller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frolic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Frolic
<hw>Frol"ic</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A wild prank; a flight
of levity, or of gayety and mirth.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He would be at his <qex>frolic</qex> once again.</q>
<rj><qau>Roscommon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A scene of gayety and mirth, as in lively play, or
in dancing; a merrymaking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frolic</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Frolic
<hw>Frol"ic</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Frolicked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Frolicking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To play wild pranks; to play
tricks of levity, mirth, and gayety; to indulge in frolicsome play; to
sport.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hither, come hither, and <qex>frolic</qex> and play.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Frolicful</ent>⟦br⟧
